To achieve this, you can write a C++ program that accepts input from the command line and then outputs the student's name, grade, and an adjective based on their performance. You can then run this compiled C++ program from a shell command. Here's a simple C++ code snippet that demonstrates this:

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

std::string getPerformanceAdjective(int grade) {
    if (grade >= 90) {
        return "outstanding";
    } else if (grade >= 75) {
        return "excellent";
    } else if (grade >= 50) {
        return "good";
    } else {
        return "needs improvement";
    }
}

int main(int argc, char* argv[]) {
    if (argc != 3) {
        std::cerr << "Usage: " << argv[0] << " <name> <grade>" << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::string name = argv[1];
    int grade = std::stoi(argv[2]);

    std::string performance = getPerformanceAdjective(grade);

    std::cout << "Student Name: " << name << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Grade: " << grade << "%" << std::endl;
    std::cout << "Performance: " << performance << std::endl;

    return 0;
}
```

Here's how you can compile and run this program from the shell:

1. Save the C++ code to a file, say `student_performance.cpp`.
2. Compile the code using a C++ compiler like g++:

   ```bash
   g++ -o student_performance student_performance.cpp
   ```

3. Run the compiled program with the student's name and grade as arguments:

   ```bash
   ./student_performance Alice 100
   ```

This will output:

```
Student Name: Alice
Grade: 100%
Performance: outstanding
```

You can adjust the grade thresholds and adjectives in the `getPerformanceAdjective` function to match your specific criteria for performance descriptions.
